caption: Nice park for tourists like us. Plenty of locals using it to sit and chat, but there are many benches. There are two little playgrounds, toilets, and a rotunda. Don't kick balls around, they will get stuck on the roof of the rotunda. Tried to spot a few birds, but they hid in the plentiful bushes.
Peaceful piece of green on the side of busy boulevard surrounded by neat Hausmanian buildings.

Small. Good for shelter, particularly for parents of small children ( covered seating by the sandpit and playground features), a small park where there are not many others nearby. Popular for playing ball despite its small size.
Very nice park surrounded by amazing Haussmanian buildings. Great for kids to play or for relaxing. A lot of shops and bars around. A nice to go, stay and come back !

One of the best parks in Paris. A hidden gem in the 18th district.  Perfect place for kids to play around. Gated area for kids. Big hall for when it rains too. A lot of kids from the area come to play there.  Closes at 19h30.
Nice spot for a picnic, though you will want to spread a blanket. Also good for people watching.
Lovely square but too sandy. Don't go here if you're allergic to dust
nice place to relax n enjoy
Very nice quietish park- a gem for busy Paris
Wonderful park to feel like locals
Take a rest with all those Parisian windows view.
Nice are and good restaurants around.

it is a small place, little known but very pleasant.   It is quite small but contains various facilities such as a ping pong table, a children's play area, a kiosk, table football, toilets.   It is ideal for shade thanks to the trees.

A pretty shaded square with numerous benches, kiosk and games for children. It has the particularity of also bearing the name of Square de Clignancourt. Family-friendly and quiet, its size is large, sandy soil, slender trees üå≤, flowers and bushes provide real breathing space just a stone's throw from the Jules Joffrin town hall. The square is surrounded by buildings typical of Paris, elegant, even luxurious, which make you want to live there. Today is August 25 and a tribute has been paid on the plaque (photo1) for the liberation of Paris to Maurice Kriegel Valrimont

Pretty square with trees and flowers, pleasant. In 2007, the square took the name of Maurice Kriegel Valrimont (1914-2006), former parliamentarian and resistance fighter. The garden bears the imprint of the architect Paul Morice, designer of a series of stone and brick buildings located nearby. In this square we find a bandstand, hawthorns, flowering pear trees, maples, hornbeams, paulownias, oaks, hazel trees, lime trees
Nice with a play area for little ones including a small slide and a sandbox. There are also 2 ping pong tables and a table football.

One of the most charming squares in the Jules Joffrin/Simplon district: its music kiosk dating from the last century regularly hosts a few events but it is above all these trees, some of them century-old, which will delight your break in this square. You will see a Chinese cedar, classified as a remarkable tree, planted in 1910. For a moment of freshness and contemplation, this square is perfect.
Very pleasant place in the 18th arrondissement. A little haven of tranquility with lots of greenery, games for children and the cherry on the cake: a kiosk.
My children are 40 years old and I was already going there with them. My grandson continues the tradition...

Nice garden in the middle near one of the avenues in the 18th neighborhood of Paris, once we pass the door the noise recedes, a garden with beautiful trees currently in bloom. At the back there is a sandpit and park for children up to 8 years old and next to it there are climbing ropes for older children and in the center a kiosk for small shows.
Beautiful, clean city park surrounded by pretty house facades. There is also plenty of seating.

Cozy place in the shade hidden behind beautiful buildings with the classic balconies. I missed a little more play racks. For example, something that could spin around, a larger slide, Trampoline or the like. Unfortunately, the toilets were also locked.

Small haven of peace in the 18th century, well-maintained park perfect for walking, recharging your batteries, reading a book or chatting on the many benches offered. Small play area for children as well. A few meters from the Jules Joffrin station and town hall, therefore easily accessible whether by metro or bus.
Beautiful and quiet square located in a classic bourgeois district of Paris.
